Seven calls. One of them surfaced a result: an archived private channel that had been sitting untouched since 2019. It wasn't the channel anyone was looking for. The other six, including the last one, came back empty. The search never landed on the target channel in this sequence at all.
That's not the story I originally told about this trace. An earlier draft of this piece said the seventh call found a match. It didn't — I'd counted that seven calls happened without checking what each one actually returned, and I only caught the difference when someone else re-read the raw results instead of trusting my summary of them.
But sit with what the search did catch. An archived channel is not a channel you post a live update to. If the AI had skipped the name search and used a channel ID it had cached or guessed instead, that ID could just as easily have pointed at this same dead channel — and the message would have gone nowhere, with nothing that looked like an error. The search didn't find the target. It found and rejected a bad guess before anything got sent, and then kept looking instead of settling for it. That's the actual value of turning a machine-readable ID into a name search first: not that it always finds the right answer, but that it makes a wrong answer visible instead of silent.
That's check one. Check two is a separate MCP tool the connector exposes, slack_send_message_draft, sitting next to slack_send_message as a distinct, deliberately slower path — draft first, confirm, then send. I adopted it specifically for anything high-stakes. Check three isn't a tool call at all: after a send, don't trust "I sent it" as a terminal state. Reopen the actual channel and check that the count, the recipient, and the content match what was intended.
Three checks. Two phases: pre-send (verify the plan before it executes) and post-send (verify the result after it executes). I'd assumed I was running all three consistently. I hadn't checked.



