The zero is the number that changed my mind. The connector I use exposes slack_send_message_draft as a distinct tool from slack_send_message, and I'd adopted it specifically so high-stakes sends would go through a confirm step instead of firing directly. Then I audited my own session logs across the projects where it was available, looking for real invocations. I found none. The tool exists. It's available. It has never actually fired in anything I logged.
This isn't a hypothetical risk, either. AI agents misfiring a message to the wrong destination — a stale credential pointed at the wrong workspace, a notification channel confused with a similar one — is a real, recurring category of incident, not just a risk I'm imagining for the sake of the argument. That's exactly why "the draft tool exists but I've never used it" isn't a comfortable thing to find in an audit — it's a real, closable gap sitting next to a failure mode that's well known to happen.
I'd been treating "it worked" and "I can verify what it did" as the same claim about an AI action. They're not, and the gap between them splits cleanly into two different problems.
"It worked" and "I can verify what it did" are two different claims about the same AI action. Confirming the plan before execution closes the specification gap. Confirming the result after execution closes the verification gap. Most setups — mine included — only reliably close one of them.
An AI that runs correctly every time is not automatically an AI whose actions you can check after the fact. Those are different design axes. The pre-send half (name search before using an ID, draft before a high-stakes send) closes the specification gap — did the AI understand what I actually wanted it to do. The post-send half (reopening the channel, checking it matches) closes the verification gap — can I confirm what it actually did, independent of what it told me. Building the first without the second gets you an AI that's confidently wrong in a way nobody catches.
I'd assumed I was running all of this consistently. The audit only confirmed that for the one piece I could actually count: the draft-confirm step had zero logged uses. The post-send channel check isn't a tool call, so I don't have the same kind of number for it — I don't have a clean way to prove I'm doing it every time, which is itself worth sitting with. The one gap I could measure turned out to be real. I can't yet tell you the other one isn't.
The 2-phase idea should generalize past Slack: something checkable before an action executes, and something checkable after. The specific mechanism here — a name search in front of an ID — is Slack-shaped, because Slack happens to expose both a machine ID and a human-searchable name for the same channel. Other tools won't have that exact shape. The underlying question does travel, though.
If the AI is about to use a machine-readable identifier for an action with a real side effect, ask whether there's a human-checkable equivalent you can force it through first. For Slack that's a name search. For your tool it'll look different — but the question is the same one.
If the action is high-stakes and hard to undo in practice, gate it behind an explicit draft-and-confirm step — and then actually check your logs for whether that step ever fires, the way I hadn't.
After the action runs, don't accept "done" as the end of the story. Reopen the actual system state and check it against what you intended.
What's the smallest post-action check you could add before trusting your AI's next "sent successfully" — and have you actually looked at your logs to see whether you're running it, or just assuming you are, the way I was?
Sho Naka (nomurasan). I ship, and I've learned the hard way that counting how many times a tool was called is not the same as checking what it actually returned.
This piece draws on a Japanese essay covering the same underlying mechanisms, rewritten from scratch as an implementation log (not a direct translation) with AI assistance for structure and the cross-language rewrite. An earlier draft of this piece contained a factual error in its central trace: it described the search sequence as ending in a match, and it doesn't. That was caught by an independent adversarial review of the raw logs, not by the first read-through. The tool-call counts, the audit results, and the conclusions in this version are mine, checked against the individual results of my own session logs — not just the fact that a tool was called.

As the discussion around Artificial Intelligence shifts from generative hype to financial sustainability, I wanted to build a dedicated tool to track the "bubble status" of AI-related equities.
Instead of spinning up a heavy Kubernetes cluster or paying for expensive enterprise data pipelines, my goal was to build a highly responsive, SEO-optimized, and low-latency metrics dashboard.
Here is the architectural breakdown of how I built AI Stock Bubble Index.
The Architecture: Keeping it Lightweight
Frontend Framework: Built entirely with a components-driven framework (React) to ensure instant UI state updates when users toggle different tracking metrics.
Data Ingestion: Instead of keeping an active database connection open for every single visitor, market volatility metrics and structural data schemas are processed asynchronously and served via highly optimized JSON endpoints.
Styling & Interactivity: Leveraged highly responsive UI kits alongside custom CSS logic to ensure smooth rendering of data charts across both desktop and mobile viewports.
Technical Challenge 1: Micro-Frontend SEO & Indexing
To tackle this:
Semantic HTML Layouts: I structured the FAQs and dashboard summaries using strict semantic markup rather than nested 
 soup.

Sitemap & Index Management: Implemented an automated build pipeline that updates the indexation status and alerts search consoles whenever market thresholds trigger significant index shifts.
Technical Challenge 2: Client-Side Data Rendering Efficiency
// A snippet of how data structural layers are evaluated before canvas rendering
export const evaluateBubbleIndex = (metrics) => {
  const { peRatio, sentimentScore, capitalInflow } = metrics;
  // Weighted algorithmic formula to determine the current market exposure
  return (peRatio * 0.5) + (sentimentScore * 0.3) + (capitalInflow * 0.2);
};

By decoupling the layout state from the heavy charting canvas, the page achieves an exceptionally high performance score, keeping cumulative layout shifts (CLS) near zero.
